'''Gina Cerminara''' (April 11, 1914 – April 1984) was an American author in the fields of [[parapsychology]], [[spirituality]] and [[reincarnation]]. She was born in [[Milwaukee]] and received BA, MA, and Ph.D. degrees in [[psychology]] from the [[University of Wisconsin–Madison]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Religion Notes|date=Sep 2, 1978|publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/24613784.html?dids=24613784:24613784&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=May+17%2C+1987&author=Paul+Galloway&pub=Chicago+Tribune+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&desc=THE+SEARCH+FOR+PAST+LIFE+REINCARNATION%27S+BELIEVERS+LOOK+AT+THE+WAYS+THEY+WERE|title=THE SEARCH FOR PAST LIFE REINCARNATION'S BELIEVERS LOOK AT THE WAYS THEY WERE|last=Galloway|first=Paul |date=May 17, 1987|publisher=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=2009-09-07}}</ref> Her years of [[research]] regarding [[Edgar Cayce]] led her to publish a book about reincarnation in 1950 titled ''[[Many Mansions]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Cranston|first=S. L. |title=HPB: the extraordinary life and influence of Helena Blavatsky, founder of the modern Theosophical movement|publisher=Path Pub. House, |year=1998|page=505|isbn=978-0-9662115-1-1}}</ref> Her other books on [[reincarnation]] include ''The World Within'', ''Many Lives, Many Loves'' and ''Insights for the Age of Aquarius''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Johnson|first=K. Paul |title=Edgar Cayce in context: the Readings, truth and fiction SUNY series in Western esoteric traditions|publisher=[[SUNY Press]]|year=1998|page=161|isbn=978-0-7914-3905-0}}</ref>
