This is a '''list of victims of the [[Babi Yar massacre]].''' During September 29—30, 1941, a special team of [[Nazi Germany|German]] [[Schutzstaffel|SS]] aided by [[Ukrainian-German collaboration during World War II|Ukrainian police]] killed 33,771 [[Jew]]s. Subsequent massacres also included [[Ukrainians|Ukrainian]]s and [[Poles]].<ref name="USHMM">[[United States Holocaust Memorial Museum]], [http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/ Holocaust Encyclopedia] after taking them to the ravine. [http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/article.php?lang=en&ModuleId=10005421 Kiev and Babi Yar]</ref><ref>''A Community of Violence: The SiPo/SD and Its Role in the Nazi Terror System in Generalbezirk Kiew'' by Alexander V. Prusin. Holocaust Genocide Studies, Spring 2007; 21: 1 - 30.</ref> The Babi Yar massacre is considered to be "the largest single massacre in the history of [[the Holocaust]]".<ref>[http://moses.creighton.edu/JRS/pdf/2007-18.pdf From Berlin to Babi Yar. The Nazi War Against the Jews, 1941-1944] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090305074504/http://moses.creighton.edu/JRS/pdf/2007-18.pdf |date=2009-03-05 }} by Wendy Morgan Lower, [[Towson University]]. ''Journal of Religion & Society'', Volume 9 (2007). The Kripke Center IS.S.N 1522-5658</ref> Executions of Jews, [[Ukrainians]], [[Romani people|Gypsies]] and others continued in Babi Yar throughout the period of the Nazi occupation of [[Kiev]], ending with the beginning of the [[Battle of Kiev (1943)]], totalling up to 120,000 victims.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}
